---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Affiliate Disclosure — Quvii"
  description="How Quvii uses affiliate links — primarily Amazon Associates for cross-referenced security camera recommendations. Editorial independence policy and how to spot an affiliate link."
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-ink">Affiliate Disclosure</h1>
  <p class="text-sm text-body-faint">Last updated: 2026-05-27</p>

  <div class="prose-pm max-w-prose">
    <p class="lead">
      Some links on Quvii's blog earn us a commission when you click through
      and buy. This page tells you which programs we participate in, how to
      identify an affiliate link, and how we keep recommendations honest.
    </p>

    <h2>What we participate in</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Amazon Associates</strong> (Associate ID <code>jeffzen911-20</code>).
        When we recommend a competitor camera (Eufy, Ring, Reolink, Blink, Arlo,
        Wyze, etc.) in a comparison or buying guide, we link to it on Amazon.
        If you buy after clicking, Amazon pays us a small percentage. The
        price you pay is the same as if you'd gone to Amazon directly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Quvii own products</strong>. Links to Quvii's own cameras
        on this site are first-party links to our own store, not affiliate
        links. We make the margin on the product itself.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We don't currently participate in any other affiliate program. If that
      changes, this page is updated and the change is logged in the
      "Last updated" date at the top.
    </p>

    <h2>How to spot an affiliate link</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>The link tag carries <code>rel="sponsored noopener nofollow"</code>
        — the FTC + Google standard for paid placements at the HTML level.</li>
      <li>The URL contains our Amazon Associate ID
        (<code>tag=jeffzen911-20</code>). Hover over any "Check on Amazon"
        button and look at your browser's status bar.</li>
      <li>Articles with affiliate links display a yellow "Affiliate disclosure"
        banner at the top of the page (this same text, summarized).</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Editorial independence</h2>
    <p>
      Our commission rate from Amazon (typically 1-4% of purchase price) is
      the <em>same percentage</em> across compared products in a category.
      That means we earn the same whether we put Product A or Product B at #1.
      The ranking is editorial, not financial.
    </p>
    <p>What we won't do, regardless of commission rate:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Recommend a product we wouldn't use ourselves.</li>
      <li>Hide cons. Every product gets weaknesses called out.</li>
      <li>Re-order rankings in exchange for a higher rate.</li>
      <li>Publish a press release as a review.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What if I don't want to use an affiliate link?</h2>
    <p>
      Go to amazon.com directly and search for the product name. The price
      is identical, we don't earn anything, and you skip the cookie. We'd
      still rather you came through us — the writing has to earn its keep —
      but we won't penalize you for opting out.
    </p>

    <h2>FTC required statement</h2>
    <p>
      <em>"As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases."</em>
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Broken affiliate link, complaint, or partnership inquiry:
      <strong>hello@quvii.com</strong>.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
